Abstract.

For a closed symplectic manifold (M,Ï‰)ğ‘€ğœ”(M,\omega) with compatible Riemannian metric gğ‘”g we study the Sobolev H1superscriptğ»1H^{1} geometry of the group of all Hssuperscriptğ»ğ‘ H^{s} diffeomorphisms on Mğ‘€M which preserve the symplectic structure. We show that, for sufficiently large sğ‘ s, the H1superscriptğ»1H^{1} metric admits globally defined geodesics and the corresponding exponential map is a non-linear Fredholm map of index zero. Finally, we show that the H1superscriptğ»1H^{1} metric carries conjugate points via some simple examples.

Keywords: Symplectic manifold; Geodesic; Spray; Variation; Hilbert manifold; Fredholm operator; Sobolev metric; Conjugate point; Einstein manifold.

1. Introduction

A number of well-known nonlinear partial differential equations of mathematical physics arise as geodesic equations on various infinite dimensional Lie groups. The most fundamental example is the Euler equations of ideal hydrodynamics where Arnold [1] noticed that a curve Î·â€‹(t)ğœ‚ğ‘¡\eta(t) in the group of smooth volume preserving diffeomorphisms is a geodesic of the right-invariant L2superscriptğ¿2L^{2} metric if and only if the velocity field vâ€‹(t)=Î·â€‹(t)Ë™âˆ˜Î·âˆ’1â€‹(t)ğ‘£ğ‘¡Ë™ğœ‚ğ‘¡superscriptğœ‚1ğ‘¡v(t)=\dot{\eta(t)}\circ\eta^{-1}(t) solves the Euler equations of hydrodynamics. Subsequently, Ebin and Marsden [5] showed that the volume preserving diffeomorphism group can be given the structure of a Hilbert manifold and proved that the corresponding geodesic equation is actually a smooth ordinary differential equation, hence rigourously justifying the infinite dimensional geometric constructions. Since then, much research has focused on finding geometric formulations for other conservative systems in continuum mechanics. For examples of these see Arnold-Khesin [2], Marsden and Ratiu [13], Schmid [17], Taylor [19], Vizman [20], Zeitlin and Kambe [21], or Khesin-Wendt [10] and the references therein.

Two motivations for the present work are the Lagrangian-averaged Euler equations as considered by Shkoller [16] and the symplectic diffeomorphism group equipped with the L2superscriptğ¿2L^{2} metric as considered by Ebin [4].

The Lagrangian-averaged Euler equations were first introduced by Holm, Marsden, and Ratiu in Euclidean space, and describe the mean hydrodynamic motion of an incompressible fluid. Shkoller [16] realized the Lagrangian-averaged Euler equations as the Euler-Poincare equations associated with the geodesic flow of the right-invariant Sobolev H1superscriptğ»1H^{1} metric on the group of volume-preserving diffeomorphisms of a compact n-dimensional Riemannian manifold. He showed that, for sufficiently large sğ‘ s, the geodesic spray is continuously differentiable so that a standard Picard iteration argument proves existence and uniqueness of solutions on a finite time interval. Kouranbaeva and Oliver [11] have subsequently shown that when the underlying manifold is two dimensional the Lagrangian-averaged Euler equations admit weak global solutions.

In the present work we consider a closed symplectic manifold, with symplectic form Ï‰ğœ”\omega, and the group of Sobolev Hssuperscriptğ»ğ‘ H^{s} symplectic diffeomorphisms ğ’ŸÏ‰sâ€‹(M)subscriptsuperscriptğ’Ÿğ‘ ğœ”ğ‘€\mathcal{D}^{s}_{\omega}(M) of Mğ‘€M equipped with the right-invariant Sobolev H1superscriptğ»1H^{1} metric on vector fields. Our main theorem is

Theorem 1.1.

Let (M,Ï‰)ğ‘€ğœ”(M,\omega) be a closed, 2â€‹n2ğ‘›2n-dimensional symplectic manifold with compatible Riemannian metric gğ‘”g. Then, for s>n+3ğ‘ ğ‘›3s>n+3, the group ğ’ŸÏ‰sâ€‹(M)subscriptsuperscriptğ’Ÿğ‘ ğœ”ğ‘€\mathcal{D}^{s}_{\omega}(M) is H1superscriptğ»1H^{1} geodesically complete.

We note that when Mğ‘€M is two dimensional the symplectomorphism group and volume-preserving diffeomorphism group coincide so that our results strengthen those of Kouranbaeva and Oliver aswell as generalize them to the 2â€‹n2ğ‘›2n-dimensional symplectic setting.

The symplectomorphism group equipped with the L2superscriptğ¿2L^{2} metric on vector fields has already been conidered by Ebin [4] who showed that the corresponding geodesic equation is globally well-posed. In this setting the subgroup of Hamiltonian diffeomorphisms play a role in plasma dynamics analogous to the role played by the volume-preserving diffeomorphism group in hydrodynamics. In particular, the L2superscriptğ¿2L^{2} geodesic equation is equivalent to the geodesic Vlasov equation (see Holm and Tronci [7] and the references therein) and we could consider the geodesic equation of the H1superscriptğ»1H^{1} metric as the Lagrangian-averaged geodesic Vlasov equation.

Ebin [4] also asked if the L2superscriptğ¿2L^{2} exponential map is a non-linear Fredholm map of index zero which was answered in the affirmative in [3]. Here we use the general framework of Misiolek and Preston [14] for studying exponential maps of right-invariant Sobolev Hrsuperscriptğ»ğ‘ŸH^{r} metrics and show

Theorem 1.2.

Let (M,Ï‰)ğ‘€ğœ”(M,\omega) be a closed, 2â€‹n2ğ‘›2n-dimensional symplectic manifold with compatible Riemannian metric gğ‘”g. Then, for s>n+3ğ‘ ğ‘›3s>n+3, the exponential map of the H1superscriptğ»1H^{1} metric on ğ’ŸÏ‰ssubscriptsuperscriptğ’Ÿğ‘ ğœ”\mathcal{D}^{s}_{\omega} is a non-linear Fredholm map of index zero.

A bounded linear operator Lğ¿L between Banach spaces is said to be Fredholm if it has finite dimensional kernel and cokernel. It then follows from the open mapping theorem that ranâ€‹Lranğ¿\text{ran}\,L is closed. Lğ¿L is said to be semi-Fredholm if it has closed range and either its kernel or cokernel is of finite dimension. The index of Lğ¿L is defined as indâ€‹L=dimkerâ¡Lâˆ’dimcokerâ€‹L.indğ¿dimensionkernelğ¿dimensioncokerğ¿\mathrm{ind}\,L=\dim\ker L-\dim\mathrm{coker}\,L. The set of semi-Fredholm operators is an open subset in the space of all bounded linear operators and the index is a continuous function on this set into â„¤âˆª{Â±âˆ}â„¤plus-or-minus\mathbb{Z}\cup\left\{\pm\infty\right\}, cf. Kato [9]. A C1superscriptğ¶1C^{1} map fğ‘“f between Banach manifolds is called Fredholm if its FrÃ©chet derivative dâ€‹fâ€‹(p)ğ‘‘ğ‘“ğ‘df(p) is a Fredholm operator at each point pğ‘p in the domain of fğ‘“f. If the domain is connected then the index of the derivative is by definition the index of fğ‘“f, cf. Smale [18].

Let Î³ğ›¾\gamma be a geodesic in a Riemannian Hilbert manifold. A point q=Î³â€‹(t)ğ‘ğ›¾ğ‘¡q=\gamma(t) is said to be conjugate to p=Î³â€‹(0)ğ‘ğ›¾0p=\gamma(0) if the derivative Dâ€‹exppâ¡(tâ€‹Î³Ë™â€‹(0))ğ·subscriptğ‘ğ‘¡Ë™ğ›¾0D\exp_{p}(t\dot{\gamma}(0)) is not an isomorphism considered as a linear operator between the tangent spaces at pğ‘p and qğ‘q. It is called monoconjugate if Dâ€‹exppâ¡(tâ€‹Î³Ë™â€‹(0))ğ·subscriptğ‘ğ‘¡Ë™ğ›¾0D\exp_{p}(t\dot{\gamma}(0)) fails to be injective and epiconjugate if Dâ€‹exppâ¡(tâ€‹Î³Ë™â€‹(0))ğ·subscriptğ‘ğ‘¡Ë™ğ›¾0D\exp_{p}(t\dot{\gamma}(0)) fails to be surjective. In general exponential maps of infinite dimensional Riemannian manifolds are not Fredholm. For example, the antipodal points on the unit sphere in a Hilbert space with the induced metric are conjugate along any great circle and the differential of the corresponding exponential map has infinite dimensional kernel. An ellipsoid constructed by Grossman [6] provides another example as it contains a sequence of monoconjugate points along a geodesic arc converging to a limit point at which the derivative of the exponential map is injective but not surjective. Such pathological phenomena are ruled out by the Fredholm property because in this case monoconjugate and epiconjugate points must coincide, have finite multiplicities and cannot cluster along finite geodesic segments. In particular, the H1superscriptğ»1H^{1} exponential map behaves like that of a finite dimensional manifold.

The paper is organized as follows: In the next section we give the functional analytic setting for the symplectomorphism group and the H1superscriptğ»1H^{1} metric on vector fields. We then proceed to show that the H1superscriptğ»1H^{1} exponential map is a local diffeomorphism on a neighbourhood of the identity diffeomorphism; that is, geodesics exist for at least a short time, are unique, and depend smoothly on their initial velocity. In the subsequent section we show that the domain of definition of the H1superscriptğ»1H^{1} exponential map can be extended to the whole tangent space; this proves Theorem 1.1 above. In the second half of the paper we prove Theorem 1.2. Fredholm properties of Riemannian exponential maps on diffeomorphism groups is now well understood and a general theory has been laid out by Misiolek and Preston [14]. For this reason we will sketch the argument and indicate where the necessary changes occur. Finally, in section 6 we show that the H1superscriptğ»1H^{1} metric carries conjugate points via some simple examples.

3. Geodesics of (ğ’ŸÏ‰s,âŸ¨,âŸ©1)({\mathcal{D}}^{s}_{\omega},\langle,\rangle_{1})

We now proceed to form the Euler-Arnold equations on Teâ€‹ğ’ŸÏ‰ssubscriptğ‘‡ğ‘’subscriptsuperscriptğ’Ÿğ‘ ğœ”T_{e}\mathcal{D}^{s}_{\omega}. In order to prove local existence and uniqueness it is convenient to rewrite the equations in terms of the flow equation (9). We will then show that the resulting second order (geodesic) equation is a smooth ODE on the infinite dimensional manifold ğ’ŸÏ‰ssubscriptsuperscriptğ’Ÿğ‘ ğœ”\mathcal{D}^{s}_{\omega} and can be solved using a standard Banach-Picard iteration scheme.

The basic technique was developed by Ebin and Marsden [5] in their study of the Cauchy problem for the Euler equations of hydrodynamics. The proof we use here is completely analogous to the proofs given in [5] and the proofs given by Shkoller [16] in his study of the H1superscriptğ»1H^{1} metric on the volume preserving diffeomorphism group. Additionally, the basic theory for geodesics of right-invariant Sobolev metrics on certain diffeomorphism groups has been laid out by Misiolek and Preston [14]. For this reason we will give an outline of the argument and refer the reader to the aforementioned references.
